<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / High road costs criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT of Transport ends up paying an average of 28 per cent more on
road contracts than the price originally agreed, according to a report
published today by the National Audit Office.
The report catalogues a series of cases where costs have been pushed up for
the department by factors such as unforeseen ground conditions, changes to
designs and outright errors.
In one case a road bridge was designed without enough headroom for trains
passing underneath. The road had to be raised after work on the bridge
started. Total costs resulting from the bungle were Pounds 70,000 for the
extra work.
It also led to a claim of Pounds 350,000 from the contractor for delays and
disruption, and an estimated Pounds 450,000 in the cost of delays to road
users.
The report says the final cost of government road contracts will almost
always be higher than the tender price because civil engineering work is
unpredictable.
The Transport Department accepts the risks of unforeseen alterations rather
than requiring contractors to price for all possible risks.
The audit office, however, says the overruns are much greater than they
should be.
The department set itself a target of reducing average increases from 18 per
cent in 1985-86 to 15 per cent in 1988-89. Instead, the figure rose to 28
per cent and continued at that level in 1990-91.
The audit office says the department has paid close attention to reducing
the risk of collusion between tendering companies and has made substantial
efforts to ensure fair competition.
Department of Transport: Contracting for Roads. National Audit Office. HMSO.
Pounds 7.90.
Private way, Page 22
</TEXT>
