<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Plan to curb phone ads for bogus jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOUGHER measures to curb the growing practice of advertising bogus jobs via
premium-rate telephone numbers were proposed yesterday by the industry
watchdog.
The Independent Committee for the Supervision of Standards of Telephone
Information Services (ICSTIS) said unemployed people were being encouraged
by unscrupulous operators to call premium-rate numbers at a cost of up to
48p a minute.
The jobs advertised sometimes did not exist, but the advertiser benefited by
receiving more than half the cost of the call. ICSTIS has received an
increasing number of complaints about 'work' services despite a code of
conduct introduced this year to curb such abuses.
A report published yesterday by ICSTIS concluded that work services should
be banned from premium-rate lines unless they were provided directly by a
potential employer rather than through an agent. It added that companies
offending its code of conduct should be fined. ICSTIS would consider a ban
on work services if that did not prevent abuses.
ICSTIS said about 20 companies regularly provide work services. Answering
Services, based in Bracknell, Berks, which was the subject of four
complaints in September alone, refused to comment.
Review into Work Services. ICSTIS, Kingsbourne House, 229-231 High Holborn,
London, WC1V 7DA. Free.
</TEXT>
