<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Cadbury faulted by Ernst &amp; Young
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECOMMENDATIONS of the Cadbury committee on the financial aspects of
corporate governance are laudable but not feasible, accountants Ernst &amp;
Young said in an unusually strong attack yesterday.
The firm said it doubted that the present system of self-regulation was
'robust or responsive enough', raising the prospect of a US-style Securities
and Exchange Commission in its place.
The latest criticism comes days before the Cadbury committee meets to
approve a final revised draft of its report issued over the summer. The
report is due to be released in December.
The Ernst &amp; Young conclusions include:
Cadbury's proposed code of best practice will not be persuasive for
directors.
The statement of compliance with the code will be highly subjective and
impracticable for auditors to verify.
The role of chairman and chief executive should always be separate.
The committee's expectations for non-executive directors are unrealistic.
It will be difficult to find non-executive directors of sufficient calibre.
The Cadbury proposals on non-executives suggest a 'two-tier' board that may
be inconsistent with present law or effective practice.
The Stock Exchange should reduce the time before filing annual and interim
accounts to three months after year-end.
</TEXT>
