FT  04 NOV 92 / Opposition strike disrupts business in India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Market porters sleep on their push-carts outside shuttered shops in New
Delhi yesterday. A nationwide strike call by the opposition Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) disrupted commercial activity and some clashes were reported in
parts of India yesterday, Shiraz Sidhva reports. The strike was called to
protest against a decision by the government of Mr P V Narasimha Rao to
raise fertiliser and petroleum prices. Most markets and businesses in New
Delhi and the four BJP-ruled states were closed and rail and bus services
were partially disrupted. Elsewhere the call by the Hindu right-wing party
to paralyse the country was ignored. In Bombay, the office of the chief
minister was ransacked by political activists who gatecrashed the state
headquarters. In Bihar, BJP leaders alleged that police used force to
disrupt peaceful processions. The strike is part of a BJP attempt to
increase its support among farmers in a party made up mostly of traders.
