<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / An island pulled up by a Bootstrap: Incentives which
enriched Puerto Rico remain vital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VISITORS recently to the offices of Fomento, Puerto Rico's economic
development agency, were greeted by an exhibition of photographs depicting
aspects of the island's economy. Some photos, which record scenes in
factories and fields in the early 1940s, were mounted beside others showing
more recent economic undertakings.
Even the most cursory look at the exhibition forcefully made the point.
Fifty years ago this year, Puerto Rico, impoverished and backward - the
poorhouse of the Caribbean, says official literature - took a giant step
forward. The result today is one of the more industrialised economies in the
Americas. The spark was Operation Bootstrap, a web of incentives which have
lured big companies to establish plants on the island.
'Puerto Rico today without Bootstrap would be terrible,' said Mr Alfredo
Salazar, administrator of Fomento. 'We would still be struggling with
agriculture alone, and would still be facing the hopelessness of the 1940s.
This would have been an empty island as most of the population would have
left.'
The change has been, by any standard, dramatic and significant. Per capita
income has risen from Dollars 120 in 1942 to Dollars 6,500, while GNP has
grown from Dollars 287m to Dollars 17bn. Agriculture, which contributed 23
per cent of GDP in 1942, now accounts for 1 per cent and has been replaced
as the backbone of the economy by manufacturing, with the number of
industrial plants growing from about 50 in 1942 to 2,000 today, employing
155,000 Puerto Ricans, against 15,000 50 years ago.
The volume of trade has grown from Dollars 2bn to Dollars 35bn. Puerto
Ricans are now expected to live 74 years, 30 years longer than in the 1940s.
Companies drawn to Puerto Rico gained not only from a tax holiday, but from
the fact that the island, as a US possession, offered political stability,
low wages and relative proximity to the mainland market.
But Puerto Rico found itself losing business to competitors in south-east
Asia and in the mid-1970s obtained further advantages under Section 936 of
the US Revenue Code which encouraged mainland companies with subsidiaries on
the island to deposit their profits in local banks. These deposits, of about
Dollars 15bn, have become a pillar of the island's financial stability.
Puerto Rico's Caribbean neighbours, overtaken by economic and social
problems, sometimes look with more than passing envy at the results of
Operation Bootstrap. It is clear, however, that the Puerto Rican experiment
and its seeming success cannot be emulated.
Puerto Ricans are US citizens but cannot vote for a president. The island's
representation in Washington is limited to a commissioner who has no vote to
influence legislation.
'There are lessons in Puerto Rico for other Caribbean and developing
countries, although there are few parallels,' concludes Mr Pat Thompson,
executive director of the Caribbean Association of Industry and Commerce, an
umbrella for the region's private sector.
Puerto Rico's position as a part of the US is similar to that of French
overseas departments such as Martinique and Guadeloupe, and allows for
assistance which others cannot get. 'The lessons for us from Puerto Rico are
in the organisation and management of finance, and in negotiations with
major companies and industrial sectors for joint venture industrial
projects,' says Mr Thompson.
It is clear, however, that what Puerto Rico is today is more than the work
of Operation Bootstrap and the incentives contained in special arrangements
such as Section 936. Despite its giant leap over the past 50 years, the
island is still the least affluent part of the US. The average income of
Puerto Ricans is a third of that of mainland residents.
The economy is underpinned by federal transfers of about Dollars 4bn per
year under programmes such as those for medical aid and food stamps. The
island also receives hundreds of millions of dollars from rebates of federal
excise taxes and duties collected on exports such as rum.
Citizenship of the US has also facilitated easy migration to the mainland.
Mr Salazar says that while 3.5m Puerto Ricans live on the island, another
2.5m are on the mainland. This is an obvious safety valve against social
pressures, without which unemployment in Puerto Rico would be worse than the
current 17 per cent.
The fruits of Operation Bootstrap have helped Puerto Ricans answer some of
the questions about their political future. They know what they do not want.
Advocates of political independence have always been placed a distant third
when votes are taken on political status. Economic and political problems in
some neighbouring islands appear a powerful argument against casting adrift
from the US. The argument is mainly between remaining the same or becoming a
state of the union.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9783</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKEBPAAWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / World Trade News: New threat of trade war over oilseeds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE, DAVID GARDNER, DAVID DODWELL and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO, BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community and the US last night failed to achieve a hoped-for
breakthrough in their oilseeds dispute, heightening concern that the US may
announce trade sanctions and touch off a damaging trade war.
The EC-US talks in Chicago had stretched into a third day in an effort to
reach a deal before trade diplomats from the 105 Gatt signatories meet in
Geneva today.
The dispute over the EC's controversial system of oilseed subsidies is a key
issue blocking agreement in the so-called Uruguay Round of world trade
liberalisation talks.
Mr Ray MacSharry, EC farm commissioner, said the US and the EC had hit an
impasse in the oilseeds talks, although they had come 'very close'.
Mr Edward Madigan, the US agriculture secretary, said he would recommend to
President Bush that the US go ahead with trade sanctions against EC
foodstuffs.
But Mr Madigan added he was willing to continue to meet EC officials on the
issue. Mr MacSharry, too, said he was willing to have a further meeting,
though none has been set.
Mr Madigan said he envisaged that the US and EC could continue meeting on
the oilseeds dispute even if the US announced trade sanctions, which would
not take effect until 30 days later.
'We can withdraw concessions and continue to meet and I think the US would
be willing to do that,' he said.
The EC would have, 'no moral basis' to impose counter-sanctions, he added,
as it had not suffered financial injury yet in the case.
Earlier, Mr MacSharry had voiced optimistism, suggesting there was 'a deal
in the making, all the pieces are there'.
But in the end few new proposals emerged, and EC negotiators seemed
satisfied at least to have made the gesture.
Ms Carla Hills, the US Trade Representative, has already prepared a list of
about Dollars 1bn (Pounds 600m) in sanctions. Mr Madigan said a second list
might be in preparation.
US farm interests expect that sanctions will be announced at today's Gatt
meeting in Geneva and that talks will continue during the 30-day waiting
period before the penalties become effective.
US soyabean producers first filed an official complaint against the
Community's oilseed subsidies programme in 1987 and twice won their case
before Gatt panels.
Earlier yesterday, senior EC officials said that, apart from oilseeds, the
farm trade elements integral to a Uruguay Round deal were all but settled.
They were hopeful of a deal including the following:
The volume of subsidised exports would be cut 21 per cent over six years,
rather than by the 24 per cent prescribed in the Uruguay Round 'final act';
EC compensation payments to farmers, for the price and production cuts in
its reform of the CAP, would be exempt from cuts under the Round;
The US would agree to a 'peace clause' undertaking to settle future trade
disputes multilaterally through Gatt procedures;
The US would undertake to 'prevent any surge' in exports of cheap cereals
substitutes to the EC, which could undercut even the near-world market price
for cereals introduced by CAP reform.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
