<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / International Company News: RBC sets aside an extra CDollars
900m for loan losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Bank of Canada, the country's biggest financial institution, is almost
doubling its 1992 loan loss provisions to reflect unexpectedly heavy
write-downs on its real estate portfolio and other corporate loans to
customers in the Toronto area.
The additional loan loss provisions and a one-time restructuring charge will
slash the bank's net earnings for fiscal 1992 to about CDollars 100m
(USDollars 83m), down from CDollars 983m in 1991.
The bank said yesterday it was setting aside an extra CDollars 900m in
provisions for the fourth quarter of fiscal 1992, which ended on October 31.
This would raise provisions for the year to CDollars 2.1bn, from an earlier
estimate of CDollars 1.2bn.
Restructuring costs of CDollars 130m will also be charged against income.
These charges will result in a fourth-quarter loss of about CDollars 480m,
or CDollars 1.65 per share.
The bank said more than half the additional write-down applied to 'a number
of accounts' in the commercial real estate industry.
Earlier this year, RBC added CDollars 300m to its loan-loss reserves,
largely to cover expected losses from CDollars 780m exposure to Olympia &amp;
York. But this was offset by an identical reversal in earlier provisions on
Third World loans.
RBC said the remaining write-downs were concentrated among corporate
customers around Toronto, among the hardest-hit parts of Canada during the
recession.
Non-performing loans on October 31 totalled about CDollars 3.7bn, a CDollars
500m increase from three months earlier. The bank said it had classified as
non-accrual accounts those which are still servicing their debts but which
may run into difficulty later on.
RBC said it expected to maintain its dividend and that its capital ratios
remained well above regulatory requirements. It said problems were confined
to its corporate loan portfolio and that its retail, treasury and securities
businesses were performing strongly.
</TEXT>
