FT  04 NOV 92 / Government policy on mergers reaffirmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPETITION IN all sectors of the economy is 'the spur to increased
efficiency and innovation', Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister,
said yesterday.
His speech to the European Policy Forum, a rightwing think tank, was a
reaffirmation of the government's commitment to competition as the best
weapon against industrial decline.
Mr Hamilton was speaking on the day after Mr Heseltine, trade and industry
Secretary, apparently signalled a change of policy by waving through British
Airways' takeover of Dan-Air in spite of concerns about a reduction in
competition.
Mr Hamilton denied that the merger policy prevented UK companies from
becoming big enough to compete internationally. In general, the more
competitors there were in a market the fewer competition concerns there
would be.
That was not to say, however, that there could not be adequate competition
where one company had a very significant share of the market.
