<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Victory For Clinton: Democratic governor candidates win
seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEMOCRATS were faring well in the 12 gubernatorial races which took
place yesterday, with early returns suggesting a net gain for the party of
three state houses.
Mr Evan Bayh, a liberal Democratic incumbent in generally Republican
Indiana, held his office, as did Governor Gaston Caperton in West Virginia.
In Vermont, Governor Howard Dean kept the job he entered last year when
Republican Governor Richard Snelling died.
Rhode Island's Bruce Sundlun was also re-elected.
The Democrats captured three state houses, however. Mr Jim Hunt, governor of
North Carolina from 1977 to 1985, will return to the mansion after defeating
Republican Lieutenant-Governor Jim Gardner. In Missouri, Democratic
Lieutenant-Governor Mel Carnahan beat Republican attorney-general William
Webster in a race dominated by the abortion issue.
In Delaware, the Democrats also gained the governor's mansion when former
Congressman Thomas Carper won.
A brighter spot for Republicans was New Hampshire, a traditionally
Republican state where Mr Steven Merrill defeated a strong challenge from
Mrs Deborah Arnesen, a Democratic state legislator. She had committed
herself to a state income tax.
