<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Victory For Clinton: Incumbents ride out election storm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONGRESSMEN of both parties had braced themselves for a massacre of the
incumbents; in the end, however, the traditional advantages of incumbency -
coupled, for the Democrats, with the presidential coat-tails of Governor
Bill Clinton - seem to have prevailed in yesterday's congressional
elections.
The most closely contested races, of course, were also the slowest to show a
reliable result. Yet by 11pm Eastern time, only two notable incumbents had
fallen to their challengers: Senator Terry Sanford of North Carolina and
Senator Robert Kasten of Wisconsin.
Even Senator Sanford's defeat at the hands of Mr Lauch Faircloth, a
Republican businessman, was scarcely typical. His open-heart surgery a month
before the election raised doubts about his physical fitness to serve
another six-year term.
In Wisconsin, however, Mr Russell Feingold, a little known Democratic state
legislator, fought a humorous outsider's campaign to defeat Mr Kasten.
Democratic women enjoyed a triple success on the west coast as Dianne
Feinstein and Barbara Boxer won the two Senate seats at stake in California
and, further north, Patty Murray triumphed in the Senate race in Washington
state.
In the House of Representatives, some of the incumbents who had appeared to
be most at risk won re-election: in Kentucky, one of the first states to
close its polls, Republican congressmen Harold Rogers and Jim Bunning were
among the earliest to be returned, along with Democrat Romano Mazzoli.
In North Carolina, Democrats Tim Valentine and Martin Lancaster were
returned, as was Nick Rahall in West Virginia.
Congressman Newt Gingrich of Georgia, the Republican minority whip at the
top of every Democratic hit list, claimed victory in his district after one
of the most venomous campaigns.
Some pundits had held their breath for what would have been one of the
biggest upsets of all, the defeat in Illinois of Congressman Dan
Rostenkowski, chairman of the House ways and means committee; it did not
take place.
The first Senate results to be declared showed incumbents winning
re-election in Alabama, Florida, Indiana, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maryland,
Oklahoma and Vermont. Even Senator John Glenn, who had faced a bitter
onslaught from his Republican challenger, Mr Michael DeWine, over his
involvement in the Keating Savings and Loan scandal, won his race in Ohio.
Senator Ernest Hollings, too, won a sixth Senate term in South Carolina in a
close race.
On the Republican side Senator John McCain, another who had been tarred with
the Keating brush, won re-election in Arizona and Senator Alfonse D'Amato
was expected to win a fierce battle against Mr Robert Abrams in New York.
With 80 per cent of the votes counted, Mr D'Amato - who spent millions of
dollars on negative television commercials - had 51 per cent against 49 per
cent for Mr Abrams. The senator is a right-wing populist who distanced
himself from President Bush.
Mr D'Amato, although he has been investigated on several alleged corruption
charges and was even censured by the Senate ethics committee for
systematically misusing his Senate office, managed to fling plenty of mud
and received plenty back from Mr Abrams.
One of the closest Senate races was in Colorado, where Democratic
Congressman Ben Nighthorse Campbell was running neck-and-neck in opinion
polls with Republican businessman Terry Considine.
But Mr Campbell - a Cheyenne jeweller, cattle rancher and Olympic judo
champion who is the only Native American in Congress - edged out Mr
Considine to take the seat vacated by Senator Tim Wirth.
Early returns for the House showed mostly incumbents winning re-election.
They included Socialist Congressman Bernard Sanders, the only independent in
the entire Congress, who retained his seat in Vermont.
Results were not yet available for the sitting members who had been most
damaged by their abuse of the generous overdraft facilities of the House's
private bank.
Democratic campaign managers said before yesterday's voting that their
polling suggested a consistent 10 per cent disadvantage for incumbents;
Congressman Guy Vander Jagt, chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, who was himself defeated this year in a primary,
estimated the drag at 20 to 30 per cent.
Even without the collapse in public esteem for Congress, many sitting
members faced hard re-election battles.
US House districts are redrawn after the census every 10 years.
With population still moving from the north and east towards the west and
south, many sitting members have seen their districts dwindle or disappear
altogether.
All told, Democratic campaign managers estimate that 34 Democratic
incumbents were adversely affected by redistricting, and a dozen
Republicans.
Redistricting has brought a substantial increase in the number of districts
where most voters belong to ethnic minorities to comply with the Voting
Rights Act.
Among the beneficiaries was Ms Eva Clayton, a Democrat who last night became
the first black woman ever to represent North Carolina in Congress.
Although it was still too early to make any projection of the party
composition of the new Congress, Democratic party officials confidently
predicted that there would be no change in their party's domination of both
the House and the Senate.
Before voting began, Democrats said they expected a net loss of between 20
and 25 seats in the House, not enough to dent their 101-seat majority.
In the Senate, which the Democrats previously controlled by 57 seats to the
Republicans' 43, Republican hopes of reclaiming the majority faded long ago.
Their greatest concern in recent weeks has been whether they could prevent
the Democrats from picking up three additional seats.
The 60-seat figure would be critical to the prospects of pushing through a
legislative agenda, as it would deprive the Republicans of the 40-seat bloc
which under Senate rules is enough to sustain a filibuster and so hold up
any legislation indefinitely.
</TEXT>
