FT  04 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Last minute talks try to save consortium
offer for ITN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last-minute talks will be held today to try to reach agreement on an offer
for Independent Television News that would involve Pounds 30m in financial
support.
Representatives of all ITN shareholders will meet Mr Michael Green, chairman
of Carlton Communications, before the 3pm deadline for the expiry of the
offer.
Carlton, the television production and services company, is a member of the
four-company consortium which is offering Pounds 1 for each Pounds 1 ITN
share and promising to put up Pounds 30m to deal with a deficit of Pounds
25m over five years on ITN's London headquarters.
The other consortium members are Central Television, London Weekend
Television and Reuters Holdings. Together they would take 80 per cent of
ITN.
It is not expected that full agreement will be possible on present terms
before the deadline expires. Some companies who might sell do not like the
Pounds 1 price. Others, such as Thames, Granada and possibly Yorkshire,
which would like to continue as ITN shareholders, do not want to be
shoe-horned into the remaining 20 per cent envisaged by the proposal.
If progress is made at today's talks the deadline may have to be extended.
