FT  04 NOV 92 / People: Non-executives
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It really is the end of an era for Quicks, the once family-owned group of
car dealerships from which Mancunians have been buying their Fords since
time immemorial - or at least from soon after Ford first began assembling
cars at nearby Trafford Park in the early 1900s.
For the first time there will not be a Quick in the chair when the current
incumbent, Norman Quick, retires at the end of the year having reached the
age of 70.
In line with the current chairman's long-held objective of bringing in
outside blood to strengthen the board, he will be succeeded by Michael
Moore. The versatile Moore is chairman of Tomkins and The Bank of Edinburgh
Group and a director of Linx Printing Technologies, as well as being
chairman of the NSPCC.
Moore will serve as a non-executive director until he takes up the
chairmanship on January 1, when Norman Quick will also become Quicks' first
life president.
