<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / OFT is promised pub checklist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE BIG four brewers
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bass, Allied-Lyons, Courage and Whitbread  - have undertaken to supply
yearly details of the size and composition of their pub estates to the
Office of Fair Trading.
The information will enable the OFT to monitor compliance with the
government's orders requiring the national brewers to dispose of 12,000
pubs, about a third of their estates, by last weekend.
As a result of the orders, national brewers own 31.6 per cent of the
country's pubs, compared with 43 per cent in 1986.
The weakening of the brewers' grip  - initiated by the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission report on the industry in 1989  - was intended to
'increase competition in brewing, wholesaling and retailing . . . reduce
prices and widen consumer choice'. A report is expected from the OFT next
year on the extent to which those aims have been achieved.
The results, so far, have fallen well short of the targets. The disposal of
the national brewers' pubs has opened the retail market to many new,
independent pub companies and enabled the regional brewers to strengthen
their pub estates.
But the restructuring has cost the nationals an estimated Pounds 500m, and
in the resulting turmoil many tenants have lost their livelihoods and up to
2,000 pubs have closed.
The dispersal of pub ownership has been matched by increased consolidation
of beer production. Several companies have quit brewing to concentrate on
their more profitable retailing operations. Grand Metropolitan sold its
breweries to Courage; Boddington, Devenish, and Greenalls closed their
regional breweries.
In 1989, the six largest brewers controlled 77 per cent of production; when
the proposed merger of Allied's brewing operations with those of Carlsberg
is completed, 82 per cent of production will be in the hands of five
companies.
Competition between national brewers to supply the enlarged 'free' market
has increased; but each has maintained beer supplies to most of the pubs it
has sold or leased by negotiating long-term contracts with the new owners.
Consumer choice has been only marginally improved.
Bar prices, far from falling, have increased by 17 per cent above inflation
during the past three years.
</TEXT>
