<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / TUC delegation will meet Lamont today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the chancellor, will meet trade union representatives
today to discuss ideas for promoting economic growth.
It will be the first meeting between the Trades Union Congress and the
chancellor since the early 1980s.
The trade union delegation will be headed by Mr Norman Willis, the TUC's
general secretary, and other leading officials from the TUC's executive
council and emergency energy committee, representing thousands of employees
in the public and private sectors.
The TUC requested a meeting with Mr Lamont last month, when the chancellor
said he would be listening to the views of industry ahead of the Autumn
Statement next week.
A TUC official said yesterday: 'We are glad that he is seeing us as part of
that process.'
The TUC plans to restate the main points of its recent economic policy
statement, A Call for Action, which emphasises the need for growth. It also
wants a public investment programme and a long-term recovery plan based on
specific industrial sectors.
After 1983, when Mr Nigel Lawson became chancellor, communication between
the Treasury and the TUC was channelled through the National Economic
Development Office. Nedo is being wound down and will be abolished at the
end of the year.
The Treasury said that in spite of the demise of Nedo 'it would be useful to
have an exchange of views'.
Public-sector pay is likely to feature heavily in the discussions. There has
been much speculation in the press that Mr Lamont will announce limits - or
even a freeze - on public-sector pay increases, even though that would
involve considerable technical and political difficulties.
One TUC official said: 'If the government is going to have a public-sector
pay policy we want to know what they are going to do. Are they going to
scrap indexation arrangements or are they going to scrap the review bodies?'
TUC officials see themselves as representing a broad-based coalition of
political protest against recent government decisions.
</TEXT>
