<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / Survey warns on funds for training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS in a survey published by the Industrial Society have warned the
government strongly not to cut publicly funded training programmes and
initiatives.
Most managers, according to the survey, believed that possible cuts in
funding for Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs), which administer
publicly funded training, would damage training. Nearly a quarter said such
a move would be 'very damaging'.
Tecs, with growing numbers of unemployed, particularly the long-term
unemployed, have asked that no cuts be made to their budget of Pounds 2.4bn
a year. According to the survey of 528 companies, there has been a dip over
the past six months in training spending by companies.
Many trade unions would like to negotiate on training, but the survey said
that only 6 per cent of managers in the survey treated training as a matter
for negotiation with unions and only a further 2 per cent were considering
it.
Nearly two thirds of the companies surveyed described their companies as
largely 'traditional' at present in terms of industrial relations, but 52
per cent expected their companies to cut management layers and move towards
'empowering' individuals.
Training Trends No 6. Industrial Society, 3 Carlton House Terrace, London
SW1Y 5AF. Pounds 20.
