<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / Dilemma at the pits as payout time ticks away: Miners are
taking sides over whether to apply for redundancy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, CHRIS TIGHE and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINERS at the 10 pits where British Coal has given 90-day statutory notice
of closure face a dilemma. Should they take redundancy now, thereby
improving their chances of getting a new job before their pit is formally
closed, or hope to strengthen the union campaign against closure by staying
put?
Neither choice in itself guarantees a stable future, but already miners are
taking sides. Of the 7,350 employed at the 10 pits, more than 1,000 have
applied for voluntary redundancy. The majority, encouraged by the wave of
popular support, have closed ranks behind their union officials, pledging to
dig in above ground if not below.
Many miners at the 10 remain fearful that by opting to stay put on basic pay
for 90 days, pending a final decision, they might diminish their redundancy
pay, as pay-offs are partly based on their last 12 weeks' wages including
overtime and bonuses.
British Coal has assured miners that redundancy pay will be based on the
last 12 weeks of full work, whenever closure comes, but many remain
unconvinced. 'You can't trust anything Heseltine says, nor any of them,'
said power loader Mr Terry Greener as he left Vane Tempest colliery in
County Durham after the last coal-producing shift on Friday.
The National Union of Mineworkers fears that a surge in the numbers of
miners already volunteering to leave the pits may jeopardise the chance of a
reprieve for any of the 10 and is seeking written confirmation of the
redundancy assurance. 'We're facing a flight of men from the colliery,' said
Mr Tony Mitchell, NUM assistant secretary at Vane Tempest.
What is the financial outlook for miners who take redundancy either now or
later if, after the 90-day review, their pit is closed?
Redundancy pay accounts for about three quarters of the original Pounds 1bn
earmarked to cushion the closure blow, but the sums available are far less
generous than those available until March 1987, when the maximum pay-out was
about Pounds 80,000.
Under the present programme, total redundancy payments (made up of statutory
minimum redundancy and British Coal redundancy) range from Pounds 3,760
(19-year-old miner with three years of service and average weekly earnings
of Pounds 140) to Pounds 37,000 (57-year-old miner with 41 years of service
and average weekly earnings of Pounds 300).
British Coal says that while the maximum amount payable to employees is
Pounds 37,000, the average pay-out will be nearer Pounds 28,000. That is
because the older mineworkers have long since left the industry, leaving an
industry with an average age profile of 36 to 37 years.
British Coal refuses to make available detailed figures on the number of
miners that will fall into specific categories within the programme.
The NUM argues that in practice the programme will disadvantage many young
miners, who will be paid much less that the average that British Coal
claims.
If the miners were to go on strike, they might lose their lump sum
supplements and the British Coal redundancy payment (the bulk of the
package), although they would still be entitled to a minimum statutory
redundancy. The NUM believes it would be most unusual to withdraw redundancy
pay in such circumstances and that it might be able to challenge it in the
courts.
Minimum statutory payments are as follows: age 18 to 21 years, half a week's
wages for every year of service; 22 to 54, a week's wage; 55 years and over,
1 1/2 weeks' wages.
The following examples give an indication of what miners might stand to lose
in the event of a strike: based on average weekly earnings of Pounds 205, a
50-year-old miner with 20 years' service would be left with Pounds 5,022,
while a 23-year-old with seven years' service would end up with as little as
Pounds 615. The government's Pounds 1bn fund to ease the closures is also
intended to be used on pension enhancement, which will allow miners to begin
drawing payments from age 50 rather than 60, the present minimum.
Those in the Mineworkers Pension Scheme who choose to remain in it will have
their deferred pensions increased annually. On the government-guaranteed
portion  - worth about 20 per cent of each pension  - increases will be
equal to those of national average earnings. The remainder will be increased
with the retail prices index, which is typically up to 2 percentage points
lower.
Miners will be entitled to a 60th of their final salary for every year of
membership in the scheme. Thus a 35-year-old miner with 15 years of service
will be entitled to only a quarter of the pension he would have had at 60
had he stayed long enough to collect it.
Meanwhile, miners are free to extract their pensions in a single lump sum
and purchase a personal pension  - a move that will produce less attractive
returns because, among other things, the pension payments will not rise with
inflation.
Mr Paul Trickett, secretary to the Mineworkers Pension Scheme, notes that
personal pensions do not offer death benefits or widows' pensions. 'We've
had several men who have been killed on the job who had bought personal
pensions. Their wives got no insurance benefits,' he said. In one instance,
the National Union of Mineworkers was able to extract an Pounds 11,000
insurance payment for one widow, but had been less successful in other
cases, he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
