<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / Smith visits Vane Tempest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR LEADER John Smith, accompanied by Durham miners general secretary
David Hopper, yesterday visited the threatened County Durham colliery of
Vane Tempest, Chris Tighe writes.
Mr Smith urged the public to keep up the pressure on the government to
reverse the 'foolish' decision to close 31 collieries.
In the first of a series of visits by senior opposition politicians to every
coalfield in Britain, Mr Smith challenged the prime minister to go to see at
first hand the impact of the proposed closures on Britain's energy reserves
and on mining communities. He said coal was one of Britain's important
energy resources but the government had 'rigged' the market after
electricity privatisation.
'It's a deliberate result of the electricity privatisation and the dash for
gas,' he said. 'It's folly from the national interest point of view, and
it's the government we look to to protect our national interest.'
Mr Smith, wearing a Coal Not Dole sticker, said he had come to the Durham
coalfield to show that Labour was standing fully behind the miners and their
communities in their campaign.
After a brief meeting with Mr Tony Gray, Vane Tempest colliery manager, he
met miners from Westoe and Wearmouth collieries in Tyne and Wear, among the
21 pits whose future will be decided by the government's review, and from
Vane Tempest, which has slim prospects beyond the present 90-day
consultation period. In nearby Easington he met miners' families and
community and church leaders.
British Coal says 215 of Vane Tempest's 870 miners have taken voluntary
redundancy in the past three weeks and another 12 have transferred jobs.
</TEXT>
