<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / Officials 'defeatist' on Rosyth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office was accused yesterday of taking a defeatist attitude to
the possible closure of the Rosyth naval dockyard when it emerged that
Scottish Enterprise, the development body, is drawing up contingency plans
for alternative uses of the facility.
Scottish Enterprise and the local enterprise companies have been considering
alternative uses for the Rosyth dockyard site, including a business park and
an industrial estate.
A plan for building a roll-on roll-off ferry terminal on land next to the
naval base and adjoining the dockyard is also being examined, although that
could be set up even if the dockyard stays open.
The government should decide shortly whether work on maintaining the new
Trident submarines should go to Rosyth, operated by the Babcock-Thorn
consortium, or to the larger naval dockyard at Devonport in Plymouth. Some
Pounds 120m has already been spent preparing Rosyth as a repair facility for
the submarines.
It is thought that whichever yard loses the Trident work would have to
close. In Rosyth's case, that would involve the loss of 4,000 jobs.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor and Labour MP for Dunfermline East which
includes Rosyth, said the Scottish Office should step up its fight to
persuade the Ministry of Defence to keep Rosyth open, rather than plan for
the aftermath of closure. It was doing things in the wrong order.
He also rejected as unacceptable suggestions in the Scottish press that if
Rosyth closed as a dockyard it could still be used for the dismantling of
the navy's nuclear-powered submarines. Three decommissioned hunter-killer
submarines and one Polaris submarine are already moored in the dockyard.
For Rosyth both to lose its dockyard and become a 'nuclear graveyard' was
unacceptable to Scotland, he said.
Scottish Enterprise said contingency planning for 'a variety of
eventualities' was sensible in the light of 'recent press speculation'.
</TEXT>
