<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / MI5 told of plan for Iraqi gun 'in 1988'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH security was first told in May 1988 that Iraq was planning to build
a gun capable of firing large shells, it was claimed at the Old Bailey
yesterday.
Mr Mark Gutteridge, an employee of Matrix Churchill, the machine tool
manufacturer, told MI5 then about Iraqi plans to co-operate with SRC, the
company run by the late Mr Gerald Bull, to build a 210mm shell, Mr Geoffrey
Robertson QC told the court.
'This was the first inkling of the supergun, ' he said.
An MI5 officer, giving evidence anonymously, said Mr Gutteridge, his
contact, had talked to him about SRC but he could not now remember details
of the conversation.
Their relationship was typical of those between MI5 and businessmen, he said
 -a fine balance of asking for help for the best of reasons and the possible
commercial consequences.
Three former Matrix Churchill directors, Mr Paul Henderson, Mr Trevor
Abraham and Mr Peter Allen, all deny breaching export regulations by
pretending that machine tools exported to Iraq were for civil, not military,
use.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
