<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 92 / Observer: Bondage
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
So how do these canny US hedge funds, which have been increasingly
recognised as a powerful force in the world's financial markets, devise
their trading strategies?
Well, from the current US edition of Penthouse for starters. One fund has
seized on the magazine's interview with Gennifer Flowers, the one-time
cabaret singer who has been alleging that she had a 12-year affair with US
presidential candidate Bill Clinton.
The funds' traders wanted to know what view they should take of the US bond
market in the event of a Clinton win. So they sent off to a professional
psychoanalyst the 16-page article, during the course of which Flowers goes
into fulsome detail about her alleged relationship.
It was returned with the seminal conclusion that the Democratic candidate
likes to be pushed around. And what does that mean for financial markets? A
sell for bonds and good news for the stock market, of course.
